Given:
$$
\begin{aligned}
1\text{ decagram}=10\text{ grams} \\1,000 \text{ milligrams}=1 \text{ gram}
\end{aligned}
$$
We need to find how many 1-milligram doses are there in one 2-decagram container. \\
Since there are $10$ grams in one decagram, we can find how many grams in one 2-decagram container: 
$$
\begin{aligned}
2\text{ decagrams}\times 10 \frac{\text{grams}}{\text{decagram}}&=20 \text{ grams}
\end{aligned}
$$
Since there are $1,000$ milligrams in one gram, we can convert grams to milligrams:
$$
\begin{aligned}
20\text{ grams}\times 1 \frac{000\:\text{milligrams}}{\text{gram}} &=20,000 \:\text{milligrams}
\end{aligned}
$$
Since there are $1$ milligram per dose, we can divide the total number of milligrams by $1$ to get the number of doses:
$$
\begin{aligned}
20,000 \:\text{milligrams}\div 1 \:\frac{\text{milligram}}{\text{dose}} &=20,000 \:\text{doses}
\end{aligned}
$$
Therefore, there are $20,000$ 1-milligram doses in one 2-decagram container. \\
